04946nam a22008055i 9780823265077DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232650777 a10.1515/97808232650772doi  a(DE-B1597)555047  a(OCoLC)914229943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a822.3/31 aPye, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Storm at Sea :bPolitical Aesthetics in the Time of Shakespeare /cChristopher Pye. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Early Modern Political Aesthetics -- t2. Leonardo’s Hand: Mimesis, Sexuality, and the Polis -- t3. Shakespeare Distracted: Political Aesthetics from Spanish Tragedy to Hamlet -- t4. “To throw out our eyes for brave Othello” -- t5. Aesthetics and Absolutism in Th e Winter’s Tale -- t6. Th e Beating Mind: The Tempest in History -- t7. Hobbes and the Hydrophobes: The Fate of the Aesthetic in the Time of the State -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Storm at Sea: Political Aesthetics in the Time of Shakespeare counters a tradition of cultural analysis that judges considerations of aesthetic autonomy in the early modern context to be either anachronistic or an index of political disengagement. Pye argues that for a post-theocratic era in which the mise-en-forme of the social domain itself was for the first time at stake, the problem of the aesthetic lay at the very core of the political; it is precisely through its engagement with the question of aesthetic autonomy that early modern works most profoundly explore their relation to matters of law, state, sovereignty, and political subjectivity.Pye establishes the significance of a “creationist” political aesthetic—at once a discrete historical category and a phenomenon that troubles our familiar forms of historical accounting—and suggests that the fate of such an aesthetic is intimately bound up with the emergence of modern conceptions of the political sphere.The Storm at Sea moves historically from Leonardo da Vinci to Thomas Hobbes; it focuses on Shakespeare and English drama, with chapters on Hamlet, Othello, A Winter’s Tale, and The Tempest, as well as sustained readings of As You Like It, King Lear, Thomas Kyd’s Spanish Tragedy, and Christopher Marlowe’s Doctor Faustus. Engaging political thinkers such as Carl Schmitt, Giorgio Agamben, Claude Lefort, and Roberto Esposito, The Storm at Sea will be of interest to political theorists as well as to students of literary and visual theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistory. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aRenaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aEarly Modernism.  aLeonardo da Vinci.  aRenaissance Art.  aRenaissance Drama.  aShakespeare.  aSovereignty.  aThomas Hobbes.  aaesthetics.  aliterary theory.  apolitical theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823265077zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823265077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823265077/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  